          "body": "Paul anchors subjective assurance in objective history. Three times he emphasizes the *before*: Christ died for us while we were still helpless (v.6), still sinners (v.8), and still enemies (v.10). Human love rarely reaches even the righteous man; God's love reaches the ungodly. The *a fortiori* logic dominates: if God justified His enemies through the death of His Son (the harder thing), He will certainly save the justified through the life of His Son (the easier). The resurrection is soteriologically necessary — 'saved by His life' (v.10) means the risen Christ continues to intercede and preserve (cf. Hebrews 7:25, Romans 8:34). The section closes with the believer's third 'exulting' (v.11) — now in God Himself."
