          "title": "Where sin increased, grace super-abounded (5:20-21)",
          "body": "The chapter's climax explains the role of the Law. The Law 'came in alongside' (*pareiserchomai* — slipped in as a secondary entry) so that the transgression would increase. The Law did not solve sin; it diagnosed and amplified it. But where sin increased, grace *huperperisseuō* — super-abounded, the rare double-compound intensifying the verb. The chapter ends with the master image: two kingdoms in cosmic conflict. Sin reigned in death (Adam's domain). Grace reigns through righteousness to eternal life through Jesus Christ our Lord. The same verb *basileuō* (reign) governs both — but the new reign is greater, the new King is greater, and the destination is *zōē aiōnios*, eternal life. The chapter closes by handing the reader forward into Romans 6, where the question becomes: if grace reigns, shall we sin that grace may abound? The answer in 6:1-2 is immediate and decisive — *mē genoito* (may it never be)."
